text:
An introductory message from Superintendent Dr. Carol Birks

Un mensage introductorio de superintendente Dra. Carol Birks

CHESTERUPLANDSD.ORG
Superintendent - Chester Upland School District

post_text:
We’re excited to welcome Dr. Carol Birks to Chester Upland School District as our new Superintendent.

Dr. Birks was chosen after an extensive nationwide search conducted by the Delaware County Intermediate Unit.

She has worked with all levels of education, from pre-kindergarten through master’s degree. She most recently served as superintendent of New Haven Public Schools in Connecticut. Prior to that, she served as assistant superintendent and chief of staff for Hartford Public Schools.

Throughout her career, Dr. Birks has served in a variety of educational roles, including a principal, teacher, adjunct professor, and executive leadership coach, among other roles.

Please join us in welcoming her.

Keep your eye here and on our website for upcoming messages from Dr. Birks and her plans for the Chester Upland School District.

El desayuno y el almuerzo para llevar continuarán disponibles en la ubicación de la escuela más cercana a usted:

Chester High School, Toby Farms Middle School o Stetser Elementary School.

Hello Chester Upland School District Family,

This is Superintendent Baughn. I am posting this to officially let you know that as per the Governor’s order, Chester Upland School District will be closed until April 13. During the next two weeks a team led by Dr. Jala Olds Pearson (Assistant Superintendent for Curriculum and Instruction), will be working on a plan for at home instruction in the event the school closure is extended.

Additionally, “tips for social and emotional well-being will be coming out 2x a week". Tips that will hopefully help you take care of yourselves during this unsettling time. Please look for those tips to appear on our website beginning this Thursday, March 26.

Grab and Go Breakfast and Lunch will continue to be available at the school location closest to you:

Chester High School, Toby Farms Middle School, or Stetser Elementary School.

A message from Superintendent Dr. Juan Baughn:

Today we encountered a tragedy in the Chester Upland community. While I can’t discuss the details, I want to let you know that school will be in session for all students tomorrow.

Our focus is helping our students and their families during this time of need and healing. There will be added personnel on hand for those who need special attention and support.

As always, the safety and well-being of our students, faculty and staff is our top priority. We have security measures in place and are committed to keeping our students safe, and we will do everything in our power to do so while they’re in our care.

If you feel that your child or family needs further assistance, please feel free to contact the school office. We will do everything we can to help you.

Today, Rodney Lavoie Jr. from Survivor spoke with students at STEM about his struggles with anxiety, depression and panic attacks after the deaths of his sister Natalie and cousin Roger, both from drug overdoses.

He and his crew of best friends – including fellow reality TV stars, Wendell Holland from Survivor, Kevin Schlehuber from Big Brother and Brice Izyah from Survivor – stressed the importance of talking about mental health, especially in urban communities where it’s often taboo.

If any students are experiencing depression or anxiety, resources are available through the school district. Please reach out to a guidance counselor for more information.

This is Chester Upland School District's Superintendent, Dr. Baughn.

This afternoon, shots were fired outside Chester High School. No students were injured during this incident. The school was placed on temporary lockdown, not because of violence in it, but because we are working together to keep our students safe and accounted for.

As always, we will have counselors and support staff available in the schools tomorrow to speak with students who need extra counseling.

The Chester Upland School District is giving its full support and cooperation to the police as they investigate.

The School District is committed to keeping our children safe and will do everything in our power to do so while they're in our care.

post_text:
Yesterday, I submitted my resignation to Interim Receiver Dr. Gregory Thornton, effective May 24, 2020.

With a new receiver being named in early 2020, this is a crucial time for the District. I want to give the new receiver the ability to start fresh with a superintendent who can grow with the District.

Since the 1970s, I’ve called this District my second home. I love CUSD, its students and its community. It will always be a significant chapter in my story, and for that I’m forever grateful.

I wish nothing but the best for everyone in this District and cannot wait to see how it and its students succeed and grow under the new leadership.

Fondly,
Dr. Juan Baughn

He spoke with students about his career and having a healthy attitude, as a part of the Student Health Impact Project. There were shots fired this morning (Friday, September 20th) in the neighborhood of CUSA and Chester High School. Both schools were placed on temporary lockdown, not because of violence in them, but because we are working to keep our students safe and accounted for.

We have counselors and support staff available in the schools to speak with students who need extra counseling.

The Chester Upland School District is giving its full support and cooperation to the police as they investigate. We have been assured that there will continue to be a police presence on campuses at dismissal today.

The School District is committed to keeping our children safe and will do everything in our power to do so while they’re in our care.

Today, we had the honor of watching a group of our students graduate from Cheyney University of Pennsylvania’s Summer Bridge program.

These students, who will be seniors in the fall, spent six weeks on Cheyney's campus, taking two courses that will grant them college credits.

This is a wonderful example of the successes our young men and women are achieving as they move forward in their lives.

We want to send a big thank you to all of the participating companies!

post_text:
A message from the Superintendent, to all Chester Upland School District families:

As you know, PSSA testing begins when we return from Spring Break. We are extremely excited for a great testing season in our district, and we want to make sure our students are feeling ready for the exams.

We ask that parents pay special attention to prompt, uninterrupted student attendance during the PSSA testing weeks, and the Keystone weeks that follow. You can help students be ready for testing by encouraging them to get plenty of sleep the night before. We want to remind you that breakfast is available for students in school. If students are feeling anxious, you can reassure them that the assessment gives them an opportunity to demonstrate their learning and helps teachers plan the best possible instruction for them.

For those who are interested, additional information about the Pennsylvania System of School Assessment is available online at www.education.pa.gov.

Thank you, and enjoy the rest of Spring Break. We look forward to seeing all of our students return on Tuesday, April 23rd.

post_text:
Message from the Superintendent (February 11, 2019):

The winter weather advisory indicated that we needed to have a 2-hour delayed opening this morning, however, many faculty and staff called out and snow continued to fall. As a result, for the safety of the students, and the lack of substitutes to fill the positions, I thought it was mandatory and prudent to close schools.

My apologies for any distress that this may have caused students, their families and staff. There are times when we just have no control of the weather and subsequent results.

Respectfully,
Dr. Juan Baughn

The Chester Upland School District added 5 new photos — at Delaware County Intermediate Unit.
June 4, 2018 at 6:08 PM · Morton ·

On Thursday, May 31st, Toby Farms Intermediate School participated in the Delaware County Intermediate Unit's Regional Math-24 Championships. Our students who competed represent the best in the building and should be very proud of their accomplishments!

6th Grade Winners Include: Alyssa Kealy, Tyhir Fields-Johnson and Tiara Lawler.
8th Grade Winner Include: Javan Montanez, Raheim McIver, and Sandra Price.

JaNiye Deedon (6th grade) and Mariama Kabbah (8th grade) both earned medals in their respective age groups. Congratulations to all our students and teachers, especially Mr. McShay and Ms. Seefeldt who helped to run the Math-24 after-school club and school-wide tournament!

post_text: A special thank you to all the faculty, staff, students, and community members who participated in our recent Orange and Black Goes Pink Event. Our hope is that this initiative will become an annual tradition here in Chester Upland as we pause each year to teach and build awareness in our schools and community about the prevention of cancer. We also would like to formally recognize the Center for Digital Learning Research Design and Resources for its generous support of the prizes that were awarded this to each school for their wonderful participation. First place winners Stetser and CUSA were each awarded a $300 donation and Main Street Elementary School, Toby Farms, Chester High School and STEM Academy each received a $100 Honorable Mention Award to recognize all their efforts. A great job done by one and all as Orange and Black Goes (Went) Pink.

Carnegie Science Center’s Mobile Fab Lab brings in-depth digital fabrication to Chester HS! Using 3D printers, laser and vinyl cutters, a Shop Bot, and more, the mobile maker space gives students the opportunity to experience the STEM-based maker movement, taking their designs from computer screens to robotic machines. From conception to fabrication, students learn how to turn "bits" into "its."

The weeklong Mobile Fab Lab experience will run from Monday, 11/17 through Friday 12/1. Chester Upland was the only district chosen in Delaware County for this unique experience for special education students!

post_text:
Toby Farms science teachers started the year off with science experiments with students!

Students were challenged to build a pyramid using paper cups. The catch? They were not allowed to touch the cups with their hands. Using strings attached to a rubber band, they needed to work as a team to stretch the rubber band, move it over the cups, pick up the cups and maneuver the cups into position without knocking down what they'd already built.

The second challenge required the students to explore principles of engineering and create a structure as tall and sturdy as possible using uncooked noodles and marshmallows. Teams came up with many different configurations and learned about which shapes were stronger than others.

post_text:
A message from our Receiver, Peter Barsz:

Formal Appointment of Our New Superintendent of Schools, Juan Baughn

As the Receiver of the Chester Upland School District, I am proud to announce that formal action was taken last night to approve Dr. Juan Baughn as the new Superintendent of Schools of the Chester Upland School District, effective July 20, 2017 through and including July 20, 2021. Dr. Baughn brings with him an outstanding reputation and a broad range of experiences in both public education and higher education. He also brings with him a long and positive history and a love of and a true understanding of the Chester Upland School District, its strengths as well as its challenges. On behalf of the students, the faculty and staff, the Board of School Directors, and the entire Chester Upland School District and Community, I ask that you join me in welcoming Dr. Juan Baughn as our new Superintendent of Schools.

post_text:
For the second year in a row, Toby Farms will represent the Chester-Upland School District at the Pennsylvania State 24-Math Championship in the Capital building, Harrisburg. Featuring over 300 middle school qualifiers from across the state, Maurice Hall (8th Grade) will showcase his talent and hard work in this mathematics-based card game.

Dakota Richards (6th Grade) also earned accolades at the 2017 DCIU’s Regional 24 Championship as a table winner. Nafir Glover, Javan Montanez, Sah’mad Fountaine (7th Grade), Tyzhon Kirlew, Ramajah Dale, and Nicole Scott (6th Grade) were chosen to represent Toby Farms after placing top three in their school-wide tournament. Staff members assisted in coaching these skilled students after school including Mr. McShay, Mrs. Santoleri, and Ms. Seedfeldt.

post_text:
On Saturday, May 6, a group of students from Chester High School participated in the 12th annual Delaware County suicide prevention 5k hosted at Ridley Creek State Park.

Chester Upland School District was also a sponsor of the event. Students learned about mental health awareness from the many sponsors who had information tents and giveaways for the participants. The CUSD group was very popular at the event, handing out cheers, and high-fives to the runners as they passed, keeping the chilly participants in good spirits. CHS students sold ribbons to bring attention to mental health awareness month, (May) and have a few more activities planned during the month. Thanks to all our students and staff who came out to show their C-Pride!

Have you heard? Starting in October, Chester Upland schools will dismiss early on Wednesdays. We're using those afternoons for teacher professional development.

Chester HS and STEM will dismiss students at 12:30 pm on Wednesdays.

Elementary and middle schools will dismiss students at 1:45 pm on Wednesdays.

Download the 2016-2017 calendar to see which days are affected, by going to www.chesteruplandsd.org (note that some days aren't affected because of professional development, holidays, or testing).
